This paper presents a framework for named entity recognition (NER) that is compatible with different languages and domains. NER is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP), which falls under the computer science category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper uses a combination of LSTM and CNN layers, which are commonly used in deep learning models for NLP tasks and fall under the sub-category of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of distant supervision, which is a technique for training models using existing knowledge bases, and falls under the sub-category of information retrieval (cs.IR). Finally, the paper evaluates the framework on datasets in multiple languages and domains, which suggests that it could be relevant to the sub-categories of natural language processing (cs.CL) and neural networks (cs.NE).
